<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1989,2016]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,153,359]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="564" pageId="6" pageNumber="563">
The eight species listed under this genus are mainly from the Holarctic (
<bibRefCitation accessDate="2019-05-01" author="ThripsWiki" box="[982,1181,1989,2015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="563" publicationUrl="http://thrips.info/wiki/" refId="ref7542" refString="ThripsWiki (2019) providing information on the World's thrips. Available from: http: // thrips. info / wiki / (accessed 1 May 2019)" title="providing information on the World's thrips" type="url" year="2019">ThripsWiki 2019</bibRefCitation>
), with six of them de- scribed from the following countries: 
<collectingCountry box="[580,648,153,179]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[662,723,153,179]" name="Cuba" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Cuba</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[737,865,153,179]" name="Kyrgyzstan" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Kyrgyzstan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[879,981,153,179]" name="Morocco" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, North America, 
<collectingCountry box="[1178,1324,153,179]" name="South Africa" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">South Africa</collectingCountry>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[1389,1436,153,179]" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Reuter)" authorityName="Reuter" baseAuthorityName="Reuter" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[243,510,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Cephalothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monilicornis">
<emphasis box="[243,413,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">C. monilicornis</emphasis>
(Reuter)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[525,589,189,216]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–12" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1890,1915]" captionTargetBox="[202,1383,184,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1390,179,1862]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–12. Fungus feeding thrips species of Iran (1) Hindsiothrips sisakhti (female); (2) Idiothrips bellus (female); (3) Hoplandrothrips bidens (female); (4) Liophloeothrips arganicus (female); (5) Hoplothrips (female); (6) Cephalothrips monilicornis (female); (7) Cephalothrips coxalis (female); (8) Allothrips bournieri (female); (9) Stictothrips farsi sp. n. (female); (10) Stictothrips farsi sp. n. (male); (11) Pseudocryptothrips meridionalis (female); (12) Megathrips flavipes (female)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3364946/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) is known widely across Europe and is reported from North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound" etAl="et al" firstAuthor="Mound" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" refId="ref7024" refString="Mound, L. A., Collins, D. &amp; Hastings, A. (2018) Thysanoptera Britannica et Hibernica. A guide to British thrips. Lucidcentral. org, Identic Pty Ltd, Queensland, Australia. Available form: https: // keys. lucidcentral. org / keys / v 3 / british _ thrips / (accessed 20 June 2019)" type="url" year="2018">
Mound 
<emphasis box="[151,199,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">et al</emphasis>
, 2018
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[319,366,225,251]" name="Iran" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Iran</collectingCountry>
, two females were taken from flowering 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Wolff" authorityYear="1927" baseAuthorityName="Lindl." box="[814,954,225,251]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" genus="Carum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="carvi">
<emphasis box="[814,954,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Carum carvi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindley" authorityYear="1830" box="[968,1073,225,252]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Apiaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Alavi &amp; Kamali" box="[1095,1337,225,251]" firstAuthor="Alavi" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" pagination="25 - 40" refId="ref5738" refString="Alavi, J. &amp; Kamali, K. (2003) The fauna of Thysanoptera in Bojnourd region of Khorasan province, Iran. Thrips, 2, 25 - 40." type="journal article" year="2003">Alavi &amp; Kamali 2003</bibRefCitation>
), and the species was also recorded from barley in Gorgan (
<bibRefCitation author="Alavi" box="[707,899,261,287]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Alavi" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref5771" refString="Alavi, J., Zur Strassen, R. &amp; Bagherani, N. (2007) Thrips (Thysanoptera) species associated with wheat and barley in Golestan province, Iran. Journal of Entomological Society of Iran, 1, 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="2007">
Alavi 
<emphasis box="[777,833,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Bagnall" authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1926" box="[918,1121,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Cephalothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coxalis">
<emphasis box="[918,1029,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">C. coxalis</emphasis>
Bagnall
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1137,1203,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–12" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1890,1915]" captionTargetBox="[202,1383,184,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1390,179,1862]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–12. Fungus feeding thrips species of Iran (1) Hindsiothrips sisakhti (female); (2) Idiothrips bellus (female); (3) Hoplandrothrips bidens (female); (4) Liophloeothrips arganicus (female); (5) Hoplothrips (female); (6) Cephalothrips monilicornis (female); (7) Cephalothrips coxalis (female); (8) Allothrips bournieri (female); (9) Stictothrips farsi sp. n. (female); (10) Stictothrips farsi sp. n. (male); (11) Pseudocryptothrips meridionalis (female); (12) Megathrips flavipes (female)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3364946/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) was described from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[251,328,297,323]" name="France" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">France</collectingCountry>
, but it is also recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[632,676,297,323]" name="Iran" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Iran</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[726,825,297,323]" name="Morocco" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">Morocco</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Alavi &amp; Kamali" box="[838,1077,297,323]" firstAuthor="Alavi" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" pagination="25 - 40" refId="ref5738" refString="Alavi, J. &amp; Kamali, K. (2003) The fauna of Thysanoptera in Bojnourd region of Khorasan province, Iran. Thrips, 2, 25 - 40." type="journal article" year="2003">Alavi &amp; Kamali 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Minaei &amp; Mound" box="[1087,1341,297,323]" firstAuthor="Minaei" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" pagination="107 - 117" refId="ref6694" refString="Minaei, K. &amp; Mound, L. (2014) The Liothrips - lineage of thrips (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae) from Iran with the first record of micropterous morph of a Liothrips species. Zootaxa, 3889 (1), 107 - 117. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3889.1.6" type="journal article" year="2014">Minaei &amp; Mound 2014</bibRefCitation>
). During the present study a few wingless specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1926" box="[662,772,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Cephalothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="564" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coxalis">
<emphasis box="[662,772,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="564">C. coxalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected from leaf litter in Fars province.
</paragraph>
